H.B. 442
GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF NORTH CAROLINA
Mar 18, 2025
SESSION 2025
HOUSE PRINCIPAL CLERK
H D
HOUSE BILL DRH30208-MH-25
Short Title: Restore Flounder/Red Snapper Season. (Public)
Sponsors: Representative Iler.
Referred to:
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO RESTORE RECREATIONAL FISHING FOR SUMMER FLOUNDER AND
3 RED SNAPPER IN NORTH CAROLINA THROUGH THE CREATION OF A
4 FOUR-YEAR PILOT PROGRAM.
5 Whereas, in 2024, the Division of Marine Fisheries of the Department of
6 Environmental Quality issued proclamations limiting the recreational harvest of summer
7 flounder to four days in joint fishing waters and the recreational harvest of red snapper to one
8 day; and
9 Whereas, the recreational fishing industry contributes significantly to the economy of
10 coastal North Carolina; and
11 Whereas, North Carolina's restrictions on recreational fishing of summer flounder and
12 red snapper are more stringent than any other Southeastern state from Virginia to Texas; and
13 Whereas, there is considerable overlap in the fish population between southeastern
14 counties of the State, such as Brunswick County, and South Carolina; and
15 Whereas, higher creel and season limits in South Carolina in 2024 gives that state a
16 significant competitive advantage in the competition for recreational fishing tourism; and
17 Whereas, state policies regarding recreational catch and release reporting and data
18 analysis overestimate overall mortality, thus skewing the science on the summer flounder fishery;
19 and
20 Whereas, coastal fishing charters or individual boats report catching large amounts of
21 these species by accident and having to release them, indicating the populations are plentiful; and
22 Whereas, these unnecessarily strict and possibly unscientific restrictions on the
23 recreational fishing industry forces recreational fishing customers and captains to move much of
24 their business to South Carolina and Virginia; Now, therefore,
25 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
26 SECTION 1. Directive. – Notwithstanding G.S. 113-221.1 and G.S. 143B-289.52
27 and any other provision of law to the contrary, the Fisheries Director (as defined in
28 G.S. 113-251), the Marine Fisheries Commission (Commission), and the Division of Marine
29 Fisheries of the Department of Environmental Quality (Division) shall do all of the following:
30 (1) Issue proclamations and undertake amendments to the fishery management
31 plan for summer flounder and red snapper in order to allow a recreational
32 season between May 15 and July 31 of each year, with a limit of one fish or
33 more per person per day, and no seasonal limit. All other size and manner of
34 take limits shall continue to apply to the summer flounder and red snapper
35 fisheries.
*DRH30208-MH-25*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (2) Revise any regulations, guidelines, or policies regarding the catch and release
2 fishery so that flounder and red snapper caught and released by recreational
3 fishermen will not be counted towards catch limits or quotas set by the
4 Division or the Commission.
5 SECTION 2. Report. – The Division shall annually report no later than August 1 to
6 the chairs and members of the House Wildlife Resources Committee and the Senate Agriculture,
7 Energy, and Environment Committee. The report will include an assessment of progress in
8 conserving summer flounder and red snapper populations and an estimate of the time line for the
9 Division to be able to increase the daily creel limit above one fish per day for the red snapper and
10 summer flounder fisheries.
11 SECTION 3. Effective Date; Expiration. – This act is effective when it becomes law
12 and expires August 1, 2029.
